instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system is built upon the Digital Shadow Reference Model, which is presented as a UML class diagram defining key concepts such as DataTrace, ProcessingComponent, and Metadata together with their associations. A concrete Digital Twin is obtained by a conformance mapping that incarnates the reference classes into specific elements (e.g., concrete processing components and model artifacts). The ProcessingComponent encapsulates the computational logic (engineering, simulation, or data‑calculation models) and orchestrates data flow: it consumes input DataTraces, applies the associated models, and produces output DataTraces. Traceability is maintained via the ‘originates‑from’ association, allowing a transitive link from any output trace back to its generating component, input traces, and models. This class‑based composition constitutes the overall orchestration pattern, integrating heterogeneous MBSE artifacts (SysML, ADLs) with processing components to achieve systematic coordination and resource management within the Digital Twin."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The DT lifecycle follows the MBSE abstraction hierarchy: (1) requirements stage, (2) functional architecture stage, (3) logical architecture stage, and (4) product/technical (physical) stage. At each stage the DT is represented by model artifacts appropriate to the abstraction: SysML requirement diagrams, SysML internal block diagrams for functional and logical architecture, and concrete engineering models (e.g., Simulink, C++ code) for the product layer. Transitions between stages are managed by traceability links defined in the Digital Shadow reference model (the “originates‑from” association) which record which processing component produced each data trace, thus enabling controlled migration of model artefacts. Governance is achieved through the conformance relation of concrete realizations to the reference class diagram, ensuring that every instantiated model adheres to the defined domain concepts."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity is addressed through a traceability chain that links high‑level SysML specifications to lower‑level simulation models (e.g., Simulink) and to generated code. The reliability of the digital shadow depends on the correctness of the underlying physics‑based (white‑box) models and data‑driven (black‑box) models, as well as on the transformations applied to the data. The approach emphasizes verification of model transformations (e.g., from SysML to simulation models) and traceability of data provenance to ensure uncertainties are identified and managed."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "Communication between the physical system and the Digital Twin is realized through MQTT, a lightweight publish‑subscribe protocol that runs over TCP/IP. Sensors act as MQTT clients publishing measurement topics to an MQTT broker; the Twin acts as a subscriber client. This client‑server topology supports low‑latency, real‑time data delivery suitable for industrial sensor update rates. The network requirements are driven by the sampling frequencies of the physical sensors (typically tens of hertz), but specific bandwidth or latency figures are not detailed in the document. Reliability is achieved via MQTT's QoS levels, while security aspects (e.g., TLS) are not explicitly described."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "The DT follows a reference‑model‑based standardization approach. A reference class diagram defines domain concepts and relationships, and a formal conformance relation (expressed as a mapping between concrete elements and reference concepts) guarantees that any concrete DT model conforms to the reference model. This provides an interoperability framework comparable to industry standards for model interchange, and the use of SysML and widely‑adopted ADLs (ACME, AADL, MontiArc) aligns the DT with established engineering standards."
]
